                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2005-03-28</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>This is a unique book. I've taken many writing courses. Natalie gets to the heart of how to actually write. If you want rules read Strunk & White. If you want to learn how to write & motivate yourself Natalie's book is for you. This book takes a "zen" approach to writing. She shows you how and where to find material to write about. How to learn to write anywhere & everywhere. How to work through various writer blocks and times when your mind rebels. The book is done with honesty & humor. It clear to me that those who pan this book have NEVER tried to write seriously. No matter whether you just want to learn to write a better journal or publish a novel, story or poem this book is a must read. </span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">Sunshine Book</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>4</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>3</span>
                      /
                      <span>4</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2005-03-21</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>So, years ago, when i was in college, we called this the "shooting sunshine up your **s book".  Ms Goldberg is unfailingly and irritatingly cheery about writing and also about the reader's ability to write, even to write well.
<br />
<br />However, in the years since i first read this book, it is a book that i refer back to frequently.  Writing is difficult.  Writing well, writing with truth, writing down to the bone, is gut wrenching.  That's why sometimes, Ms Goldberg's cheer, her certainty that it is possible, lingers in the back of my mind.  At the end of the day, the difficulty in writing is cutting thru the crap to the beautiful simplicity.  She gets it - and she'll help you get it too.
<br />
<br />So, as much as this book annoyed me when i first read it,  I'm glad I did.  It has served me well.  It'll do the same for you.
<br />
<br />Maybe we all could you use a little sunshine shot up our...
<br />
<br />Happy writing</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">Breaking Down the Bones</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>2</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>1</span>
                      /
                      <span>4</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2005-03-21</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>Writing Down the Bones: Freeing the Writer within is an example of an instruction manuel on how to write.  She spends most of the book talking about how to write, and zen... yet she never provides clear examples on how to write, and her stories are less enlightening an engaging.  Goldberg seems to have the assumption that everyone who picks up the book is a beginning writer.  Therefore she tries not to sound harsh or mean.  But as I found out after reading Stephen King's "On Writing", Honesty is the best policy.  I wish Goldberg had been honest.  
<br />
<br />Goldberg tends to throw in a lot of zen and spirituality into this book.  Sure, that's fine and dandy, but it keeps her from getting to the point!  And if I wanted spirituality, I'd go to a church or something.  All her zen stuff seems to be "fluff"  Not only that but she can't provide concrete examples.  She suggest one keep a notebook and fill out one every month.  Look, I'm not trying to write my thoughts and feelings, a poem, or autobigoraphy.  I'm trying to write a STORY.  
<br />
<br />The book aslo neglects to talk about the CRAFT of writing.  It reads like an instruction manuel (that or like a teacher that drops a textbook down in front of you and says: read it, understand it, and I'll quiz you tomorrow).  I don't want to read an instruction manuel.  I want a book that doesn't "tell" me how to write.  I want a book that talks to me, and shows me how to write.  Not one that preaches spirituality.  I'm not even a spiritual person!  
<br />
<br />Now, I'll tell you what I really don't like about this book.  It tries to be too nice when it comes to writing.  Sort of like telling a kid who really can't draw that he'll be an artist without practice.  It comes too lightly to its readers.  It isn't plain and direct, and it tries to avoid the Honest to God truth about writing.  Why does fiction work when it's good?  Why does it work when it's bad?  She never touches on what writing is!  
<br />
<br />If you're looking for a book on writing, I suggest Stephen King's "On Writing."  King isn't afraid to be honest, and he does more than preach.  He provides concrete examples, a story of how he became successful, and he actually TALKS to you through the pages.  There also isn't so much fluff in that book AND HE GETS TO THE POINT!
<br />
<br />If you're a beginning writer looking to build up your self-esteem, then pick this up.  If you're SERIOUS about writing, you'll pick up "The Elements of Style" William Strunk Jr. and E.B. White or "On Writing" by Stephen King. </span>
                  
              
